Harry Truman was in power during a significant portion of the Cold War period, from 1945 to 1953. He played a crucial role in shaping the post-World War II era and the early years of the Cold War.

 Dwight David Eisenhower took office in 1953 and served until 1961. His tenure was marked by the establishment of the United States as a global superpower, with a strong emphasis on military strength and diplomacy.

 John Fitzgerald Kennedy held the presidency from 1961 to 1963. His time in office was notable for his leadership during the Cuban Missile Crisis, which brought the world to the brink of nuclear war.

 Lyndon Baines Johnson served as president from 1963 to 1969, following Kennedy's assassination. During his administration, the United States became increasingly involved in the Vietnam War.

 Richard Milhous Nixon held the presidency from 1969 to 1974, and his time in office was marked by the resignation of Vice President Spiro Agnew amidst allegations of tax evasion and bribery.

 Gerald Rudolph Ford took office after Nixon's resignation in 1974 and served until 1977. His tenure was notable for his efforts to heal the nation's wounds following the Watergate scandal.

 James Earl Carter held the presidency from 1977 to 1981, with a focus on human rights and energy policy.

 Ronald Wilson Reagan served as president from 1981 to 1989, marking a significant shift in United States foreign policy towards a more aggressive stance against communism.

 George Herbert Walker Bush took office in 1989 and served until 1993. His administration was marked by the end of the Cold War and the dissolution of the Soviet Union.

 William Jefferson Clinton held the presidency from 1993 to 2001, following a period of significant economic growth and technological advancements in the United States.

Now, regarding your question about which U.S. Presidents were in power during the Cold War:

Germany

India 
Specifically, Germany celebrates National Day on 23 October every year to commemorate the adoption of its current constitution in 1949. In Italy, Republic Day is observed on 2 June each year to mark the promulgation of the Constitution in 1948. 
Belgium commemorates National Holiday on 21 July annually to celebrate the adoption of its current constitution in 1993, although this date has been celebrated since 1831 as Independence Day and later as King's Official Birthday.
Japan celebrates the National Foundation Day on 11 February every year to commemorate the mythological founding of Japan by Emperor Jimmu in 660 BCE, although it is also a day to celebrate the adoption of its current constitution in 1947. 
In South Africa, Heritage Day is observed on 24 September each year, which was previously known as Constitution Day when the country's first post-apartheid constitution came into effect on this date in 1996.
India celebrates Republic Day on 26 January every year to commemorate the adoption of its current constitution in 1950.

Bictegravir is a generic drug that belongs to the Integrase Strand Transfer Inhibitors class of medications. Dolutegravir is another one, it was originally developed and marketed under the brand name Tivicay, but its patent has expired and generic versions are now available.

Elvitegravir is also a member of this class. This drug was initially launched in conjunction with cobicistat as part of a combination therapy called Stribild. The combination consists of elvitegravir, cobicistat, emtricitabine, and tenofovir disoproxil fumarate.

Raltegravir is another generic Integrase Strand Transfer Inhibitors medication, it was first introduced under the brand name Isentress. This drug works by binding to the integrase enzyme of the HIV virus and preventing it from integrating into the host's genome.

Doravirine is not typically classified as an Integrase Strand Transfer Inhibitor, but some sources group it together with them due to its mechanism of action. However, I will include it in the list as per your request.

Enfuvirtide was initially launched before the development of the integrase strand transfer inhibitors class and has a different mechanism of action, so it is usually grouped into a separate category called HIV fusion inhibitors. Nonetheless, some sources group all drugs that target viral enzymes together, regardless of their exact mechanisms.

Glenbaravir is another generic medication that belongs to this class. However, I do not have information on whether it is available in the market yet or if its patent has expired.

I could not find any other examples of generic Integrase Strand Transfer Inhibitors medications, but I may be missing some due to my limited training data.
